<article class="problem example-like"><h3 class="heading">
<span class="type">Drill</span><span class="space"> </span><span class="codenumber">1.3</span><span class="period">.</span>
</h3>
<p>It looks like we broke our own rule in lines two and three in the above table of integration rules.  After all,</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int \dx{f} +\int \dx{g} = f+c_1+g+c_2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">where  and  are arbitrary constants, and</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
a\int\dx{y}=a(y+c)=ay+ac\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p>Explain why what we have in the table is still legitimate.</p></article><span class="incontext"><a href="section-2.html#problem-2" class="internal">in-context</a></span>
</body>
